{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to team-lead's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "wittgenstein-expert",
    "senderColor": "blue",
    "target": "@team-lead",
    "targetColor": "red",
    "summary": "Risk is real but small — neutralize with \"Author's translation\" attribution",
    "content": "The risk is real but small, and easily neutralized.\n\n\"Humaneness\" for 仁 is Ames and Rosemont's choice. \"Rightness\" for 义 is Van Norden's. \"Ritual conduct\" for 礼 is within the Fingarette/Slingerland orbit. These are not idiosyncratic -- they are each backed by major sinologists. The reader who knows the field will recognize them as deliberate scholarly choices, not ignorance of convention.\n\nWhat *would* look incompetent is inventing terms no one uses -- \"fellow-feeling\" for 仁 in a block quote of the Laozi, for instance. Our dictionary terms are all established options within the range of legitimate scholarly translation.\n\nThe neutralizer: attribute the block quote translation. Either \"Translation modified\" or \"Author's translation\" after the citation. This is standard practice when a philosopher retranslates a canonical passage for their own purposes -- Heidegger's translators do it constantly. It signals: *I know the standard translations exist; I chose differently for philosophical reasons.*\n\nSo: keep our terms, add \"Author's translation\" to the citation line. Risk eliminated."
  }
}
